description:
Singapore’s Covid-19 front-liners who shook off fear of exposure to infection, worked long hours and researched vaccines were collectively named The Straits Times Singaporean of the Year 2020.

They were represented by 5 people, including a nurse clinician and a swabber, who received the award from President Halimah Yacob.

"Covid-19 has united us and we have emerged stronger. The battle is not over yet but we have each other's strength and shoulder to rely on,” said the NCID’s executive director Leo Yee Sin.
Full story in bio @straits_times
📸: Desmond Wee
#StraitsTimes #Singapore #Coronavirus

In a positive scenario, the world ends up developing a vaccine that works against all strains of the coronavirus. Alternatively, vaccination ends up looking like a flu jab, where a new formulation is created on a regular basis.

In the worst case, the world remains always a step behind an evolving virus, said Mr Wong.

Link in bio @straits_times
📸: Lim Yaohui
#coronavirus #covid19 #StraitsTimes

Singapore’s Covid-19 vaccination exercise will begin on Dec 30 with healthcare workers at the National Centre for Infectious Diseases, MOH said.

Vaccinations will roll out to more healthcare institutions in the coming weeks, followed by the elderly aged 70 and older next February.

This is in line with recommendations by an expert committee that front-line and healthcare workers, along with those most vulnerable to severe complications, should be vaccinated first.

If all goes to plan, Singapore will have enough vaccines for everyone here by the third quarter of next year, said PM Lee. More details in our full story.
Link in bio @straits_times
📸: Reuters
#StraitsTimes #Covid19 #Coronavirus #phase3

Could we be seeing a coronavirus vaccine soon?
Moderna, a US biotech firm, said it would enter the final stage of its human trials for its Covid-19 vaccine on July 27, after promising early results were published in a journal.

Link in bio @straits_times
📸: Reuters
#coronavirus #covid19 #vaccine #StraitsTimes
